<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910813-0044</DOCNO><DOCID>910813-0044.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Meritor Savings Bank:   Swap Offer for $115 Million   In Capital Notes Completed</HL><DATE>08/13/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6</SO><CO>   MTOR</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><NS>BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, REPURCHASES, SWAPS (BBK)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Meritor Savings Bank said it completed an offer toexchange cash and common shares for capital notesoutstanding, bolstering its capital.   The $6.4 billion Philadelphia savings bank said about 94%of the $115 million of notes outstanding was tendered underan offer that expired Friday. For each $1,000 face amount ofnotes, holders will receive $240 cash and 180 Meritor commonshares. In yesterday's over-the-counter trading, Meritorshares closed unchanged at 75 cents a share, giving the 180shares a value of $135. Meritor said it will pay about $25.9million and issue about 19.4 million new common shares.</LP><TEXT>   The offer will boost the thrift's tangible capital by$88.4 million, to $158.9 million on a pro forma basis as ofJune 30.   Earlier this year, noteholders rejected an offer of $240cash for each $1,000 note, objecting to the steep discount.   Wilbur Ross, senior managing director at Rothschild Inc.who represented noteholders, said the agreement was the&quot;first time any of the troubled thrifts have had a successfulexchange offer consisting of cash plus stock.&quot; The accordgives noteholders about a 35% equity interest in MeritorSavings Bank.</TEXT></DOC>